post_text:
@GlenRockMSHS High School Students' Parents, and Guardians -

Information about the first day of school

‚Ä¢ September 11 is the first day of in-person classes for A Day students. B Day students will be Zooming into each of their classes to meet their teacher, hear about the course syllabus, and take part in any discussion(s) that the teacher may initiate.

‚Ä¢ September 14 is the first day of in-person classes for B Day students. A Day students will not need to Zoom into their classes for the day unless a teacher requests the students at home Zoom into a particular lesson.

‚Ä¢ On Remote Days, students will automatically be considered ‚Äúpresent‚Äù. Students will be working on assignments, readings, or projects so logging in will not be necessary unless a teacher requests the students at home Zoom into a particular lesson.

‚Ä¢ The calendar on Schoology should be used to quickly identify the designated student day.
text:

‚Ä¢ September 11 is the first day of in-person classes for A Day students. B Day students will be Zooming into each of their classes to meet their teacher, hear about the course syllabus, and take part in any discussion(s) that the teacher may initiate.

‚Ä¢ September 14 is the first day of in-person classes for B Day students. A Day students will not need to Zoom into their classes for the day unless a teacher requests the students at home Zoom into a particular lesson.

‚Ä¢ On Remote Days, students will automatically be considered ‚Äúpresent‚Äù. Students will be working on assignments, readings, or projects so logging in will not be necessary unless a teacher requests the students at home Zoom into a particular lesson.

post_text: Food drive for CUMAC Food Pantry in Paterson: A few of @GRPSHighSchool students and families are involved with a community service project. When the pandemic began, Alex and Emma Vicinanza began a food drive for CUMAC Food Pantry in Paterson. Along with the help of Carson Schraer, and Jason and Nathan Kapiloff they have collected and delivered over 2,500 lbs of food and over $1000 in cash donations to CUMAC. Even though some of the Covid restrictions have been lifted, the need for food has only gotten worse. Hundreds of people line up at CUMAC every day. They are doing contact-free pick-ups (201-572-9846) Some suggestions are cereal, peanut butter, tuna, pasta, and chili. #rockgrnj

post_text: @GRPSHighSchool "Devin Croake will be attending Lafayette College in the fall. She has been a cheerleader for the past eleven years, and loves to volunteer coach for the junior cheer program. She's planning on continuing cheer in college as a proud Leopard. Devin recently earned her Girl Scout Gold Award, focusing on bat conservation and education. She was a member of the National Honor Society, the French Honor Society, Girl Up, French Club, Relay for Life, L.E.A.P. Club, Model UN, and was a frequent to contributor to Under the Rock. She also enjoys working at Francesca's Pizzeria and enjoys scuba diving on vacation. She will miss Glen Rock High School and takes many amazing memories with her. Go Rock!" #rockgrnj #classof2020 #honoringglenrockseniors

Sallie Mae is hosting a webinar series on how to pay for college!

How to Pay the Remaining Balance: Many students and families will consider financing a portion of their college education. The focus of this session will be on encouraging responsible borrowing and what students and families can do to find the right solution for their borrowing needs.

Wednesday, June 10: 1pm-2pm EST Register https://tinyurl.com/ydgu84ts

Thursday, June 11: 7pm-8pm EST Register https://tinyurl.com/yddlcdj5

Understanding the cost of student loan borrowing: This presentation covers financial literacy topics such as the relative cost of a student loan, loan repayment tools, and tips on managing student loans. It identifies important things students should know about their loan portfolio, identifying their servicers and understanding the cost of their student loan.

Wednesday, June 17: 2pm-3pm EST Register https://tinyurl.com/y7dgqr52

Thursday, June 18: 8pm-9pm EST Register https://tinyurl.com/ya92wphy

Resources: http://ow.ly/Sd7R50zYXjD

Bard, The Culinary Institute of America, Marist, RPI, Vassar, and West Point are excited to announce their first-ever virtual Hudson River College Cruise! This collaborative and informative event about the college search process will take place on Tuesday, June 9th and Wednesday, June 10th. The "cruise" will allow students to hear from college admission experts at each institution through a series of presentations and live Q&As, all designed to help make the college search and application process less stressful and more productive. All events are open to all high school students and their families.
To learn more visit www.marist.edu/hrcc.

Best wishes to all!" #Classof2020 #seniorclassof2020 #rockgrnj #honoringglenrockseniors

post_text: @GRMiddleSchool Visual Arts 8 students with Ms. McArdle and Ms. Roche have been making extraordinary art at home - and using some surprising everyday materials! In the first few weeks of home instruction, students completed their tessellation projects using Sharpies and color pencils. Inspired by the artist M.C. Escher, these tessellations combined color blending and shading techniques to create fantastic interlocking, repeating images. Students then had fun repurposing old magazines and newspapers to create unique torn collages of food items. Last week students were creating their own homemade paintbrushes and using concentrated tea and coffee to paint a modified contour portrait of a pet or family member! #honoringglenrockartists #rockgrnj

@GRPSByrd Fifth Grade Service Project Needs your help: This year, the fifth grade class has dedicated their time and abilities to an organization called Happiness is Camping. This nonprofit organization offers the opportunity for children with cancer to have a summer sleep away camp experience. The camp is free to all campers and relies on donations to provide this experience. The fifth grade is hoping to raise enough money to sponsor a camper or two!

Here's where YOU come in - they are having a VIRTUAL 5K WALK this weekend, May 23rd through May 25th. It costs a mere $10 per walker/runner to participate. It can be done however you like - walk in the park, a jog on the treadmill, you get the idea!

Please click on the following link and be sure to write you are part of the BYRDS OF A FEATHER team in the additional info place. Share with your family and friends and get WALKING!! Register here http://ow.ly/4dbw50zNVvo

Check out the website www.happinessiscamping.org to learn more about this truly remarkable organization. #rockgrnj

post_text:
Congratulations to Mr. Arlotta @GRPSHighSchool as the winner of this year's Robert Ax Award. The staff typically votes for the honoree at the May staff meeting. This year, with the help of Ms. Bacolas, the vote was online.

Robert Ax, the founding principal at GRHS, traveled the country interviewing hundreds of prospective teachers and hiring a select few. The award was established during the 1968-69 school year by the HSA, upon Mr. Ax‚Äôs retirement.

The criteria for the award were established after consultation with Mr. Ax so that the award would recognize someone who exemplifies the qualities he valued: love of people in general and young people in particular, exceptionally high degree of personal integrity, and loyalty to colleagues, the community and - most of all - the students.

#rockgrnj

post_text: Thank you @GRPSCentral HSA which completed a community donation project using some of the remaining food day funds from the school year. The project involved several community businesses that have supported Central in the past - so we wanted to support them! We donated to Curious Reader, Gianella's, John's Boy, and Colour & Whim, and asked them in turn to donate to local organizations. post_text:
Middle School Success Class this Summer! Mr. Cece for the GR Community School.

Middle School Success: The transition from elementary to middle school can be a daunting one. Students need to adjust to a new building, multiple teachers and the ‚Äúdreaded‚Äù cafeteria and lockers. During their fifth grade year, students will experience a variety of activities designed to ease the transition from elementary to middle school. As September approaches, some students may feel the need for a refresher in a small group setting. This course offers a review of topics including locker organization, binder management, helpful homework tips and time management - reinforcing great strategies that will last a lifetime and intended for students entering Grade 6. The instructor is Anthony Cece, GRMS teacher since 2001 with significant experience in learning strategies and study skills.

Grade: Rising 6
Cost: $135
Time: 9:30 am - 10:30 am
Days of the week: Monday - Friday
Dates: August 3 - 7
Location: Virtual/Online
Register: email grcs@glenrocknj.org

College Fairs Online is still hosting our biggest virtual college yet for your region with over 80 colleges. Kevin a @GRPSHighSchool student has developed a strong knowledge and love of 3D printing as a result of the curriculum and teachers here in Glen Rock. He was surprised with a 3D printer from his family.

During this crisis, there has been a lack of protective gear for those working as first responders. Kevin decided to look for ways to help using his 3D printing skills. So, he began to print headbands for the visor that first responders need desperately. Thank you Kevin! #rockgrnj #makeadifference

post_text:
It was a banner spring in 2019 for North Jersey boys tennis players as a number of underclassmen achieved individual success and guided their respective teams to championship form.

Here‚Äôs a look at one of the boys who would comprise a so-called ‚ÄúDream Team‚Äù for the 2020 season:
@GRHighSchool Matt Shulkin, Junior

Shulkin guided Glen Rock to a 19-6 overall team record in 2019 and an appearance in the North 1, Group 1 state sectional final. Shulkin burst onto the scene as a freshman in 2018 when he helped lead the Panthers to the Bergen County small-schools crown at the second singles position. A two-time state qualifier, Shulkin reached the third round of the NJSIAA Individual Tournament last spring. #rockgrnj

Organized by Glen Rock students:
http://ow.ly/1pRU50zcUwV
"Hello! We are Glen Rock Hungry 2 Help, a local charity organization run by a group of high school students who work to find ways to give back to the communities around us. We have decided to create a wristband to sell throughout Bergen County to raise money for the health care workers fighting the COVID-19 virus on the front lines. 100% of the profits we receive will be donated to local hospitals in Bergen County to help them win the fight against the virus!

For every donation of $10, one can receive a ‚ÄúBergen, We Are One‚Äù custom wristband to show support for our health care workers. As a comment, please include your name and the address we should deliver the bracelet to, along with how many bracelets you would like to receive with your donation. If you would like to keep your information private, select the "Hide Name" option when prompted. Please email us at glenrockh2h@gmail.com if you have any other questions!"

Thank you for your support! #rockgrnj

post_text: Spotlight: @GRPSHighSchool Ms. Yancy's English 9 classes conducted a lesson involving "Interlopers", a short story. As part of a self-paced Nearpod lesson, Ms. Yancy pushed out access to a virtual field trip to the Carpathian Mountains, the location of the story. Students were able to immerse themselves in the setting, giving them a frame of reference for the read. Ms. Yancy also included all students' voices using a collaborative board for quotes about foreshadowing in the story. #rockgrnj
